I'll second that. and it works great on your real vinyl leatherette seats!  
My 53 sat in the desert for ages, good against rust but the seats got really 
dry.   It has helped restore suppleness to them. In a BIG way.   Unfortunately I 
didn't find out about glycerin until the material on  bottom of the front 
seat was cracked to bits, so it has a cover on that.  Plus glycerin is cheap and 
even good for dry/cracked skin, so no need to worry about getting it on your 
hands, it's a good idea to!   


